     1	# Phase 4: Chromatograms + Conformance Verification - Research
     2	
     3	**Researched:** 2026-06-14
     4	**Domain:** Thermo chromatogram (TIC) extraction, mzPeak chromatogram facets, conformance verification (validator gate + differential vs mzML2mzPeak + L1/L2 round-trip)
     5	**Confidence:** HIGH (every claim below verified by tool: codebase grep with file:line, pyarrow dumps of the real reference archive, and live end-to-end runs of the reference pipeline)
     6	
     7	## Summary
     8	
     9	All six unknowns are resolved by direct inspection, not inference. The TIC source is the Thermo
    10	device chromatogram API (`TraceType.TIC` via `GetChromatogramData`), reused exactly as
    11	`MzMlSpectrumWriter.ConstructChromatograms()` already calls it for the base-peak trace
    12	[file:line cited below]. The ground-truth `chromatograms_data.parquet` carries **one TIC point per
    13	scan, 1:1 aligned with the spectra** — `time` == per-scan RT (minutes, f64), `ms_level` == the
    14	originating scan's ms_level (1 or 2, **NOT 0 and NOT a fixed 1**), `intensity` == the device TIC
    15	trace value at that scan (f32). `chromatograms_metadata.parquet` is one row: `id="TIC"`,
    16	`scan_polarity=0`, `chromatogram_type="MS:1000235"`, with fully-present-but-null `precursor` and
    17	`selected_ion` structs.
    18	
    19	The validator introduces **no new structural rule** for chromatograms (there is no
    20	`chromatograms_metadata.columns.json`, and the only data-facet rule `data_kind_has_facet` gates
    21	`entity_type` `spectrum`/`mass spectrum`, not `chromatogram`). The sole chromatogram-aware checks are
    22	`cv_inflection_chromatograms_metadata` and `cv_list_declared`; both already pass because the new
    23	column accessions are MS-prefixed (already declared MS/UO). 0/0 is preserved.
    24	
    25	VER-02's reference path **works end-to-end** with the prebuilt `mzml2mzpeak` binary, but reveals two
    26	EXPECTED, fundamental divergences that the comparison must accommodate as **semantic** equivalence,
    27	not byte/schema identity: (1) `mzml2mzpeak` always writes a **chunk** layout (delta+zlib,
    28	`MS:1003089`) for spectra_data, never our **point** layout; (2) it routes **profile MS1 → spectra_data,
    29	centroid MS2 → spectra_peaks**, whereas TRFP puts every spectrum's profile signal in spectra_data
    30	(point) and additionally writes centroids to spectra_peaks. After decoding chunks and zero-stripping,
    31	the **nonzero (m/z,intensity) multisets match exactly** (verified: spec0 11057==11057, spec1
    32	14815==14815). The reference path also does **not** carry the TIC chromatogram (mzdata reads 0
    33	chromatogram points from the TRFP mzML), so VER-02 cannot diff the TIC against the reference — the TIC
    34	is validated by VER-01 (validator) + VER-04 (self round-trip), not VER-02.
    35	
    36	**Primary recommendation:** Build the TIC by capturing `(RT, ms_level)` per scan in the existing
    37	Phase 3 loop and pairing with the device `TraceType.TIC` trace (one value per scan, in scan order);
    38	emit it as the chromatogram `point`/metadata facets per the exact ground-truth shapes below. For
    39	VER-02, decode the reference chunk layout in pyarrow and compare nonzero (m/z,intensity) multisets
    40	per spectrum-index keyed by representation routing. For L1/L2, trust TRFP's own `spectra_data` as the
    41	post-read truth (no second RAW read needed). Shell out to the prebuilt arm64 binaries
    42	(`mzpeak-validate`, `mzml2mzpeak`) with skip-with-warning when absent.
    43	
    44	## Architectural Responsibility Map
    45	
    46	| Capability | Primary Tier | Secondary Tier | Rationale |
    47	|------------|-------------|----------------|-----------|
    48	| TIC extraction | Thermo RawFileReader (device API) | TRFP writer loop | Instrument exposes the device TIC trace; recomputing by summing spectra would diverge from the reference |
    49	| Chromatogram facet emission | TRFP writer (`MzPeakSpectrumWriter`) | `MzPeakParquet` (point + nested writer) | Reuse the established point-facet + cv_list mechanism; extend, don't fork |
    50	| Index/cv_list deltas | TRFP writer (`BuildIndex`/`AddMetadataBlocks`) | — | cv_list is generated from collected CV prefixes; chromatogram columns route through `Cv()` |
    51	| Validator gate (VER-01/03) | external `mzpeak-validate` (python3.11/arm64) | NUnit shell-out | Authoritative conformance oracle; test invokes it |
    52	| Differential (VER-02) | external `mzml2mzpeak` (arm64) + pyarrow | NUnit/pytest harness | Reference converter is the independent second implementation |
    53	| L1/L2 round-trip (VER-04) | pyarrow read-back of our `.mzpeak` | TRFP `spectra_data` as truth | Cheapest decisive truth is our own post-read signal |
    54	
    55	---
    56	
    57	## Decision 1 — TIC extraction from Thermo
    58	
    59	**DECISION:** Use the Thermo device TIC trace via `GetChromatogramData(TraceType.TIC)` — the exact
    60	pattern `MzMlSpectrumWriter.ConstructChromatograms()` already uses for the base-peak trace — and
    61	align it 1:1 with the per-scan `(RT, ms_level)` already collected in the Phase 3 spectrum loop.
    62	**Do NOT recompute the TIC by summing `ScanStatistics.TIC`**: the reference's TIC intensity is the
    63	device trace value, which differs from `spectrum.total_ion_current` for MS1 scans (verified:
    64	ref TIC point0 = 15245068 vs spectrum0 stored TIC = 71263168; they match only for MS2).
    65	
    66	### Where the existing writer does this
    67	
    68	`ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/MzMlSpectrumWriter.cs:917-968` — `ConstructChromatograms()`:
    69	
    70	```csharp
    71	// MzMlSpectrumWriter.cs:930-938  (base-peak; the TIC is the identical call with TraceType.TIC)
    72	_rawFile.SelectInstrument(Device.MS, 1);
    73	settings = new ChromatogramTraceSettings(TraceType.BasePeak);
    74	data  = _rawFile.GetChromatogramData(new IChromatogramSettings[] { settings }, -1, -1);
    75	trace = ChromatogramSignal.FromChromatogramData(data);   // trace[i].Times, trace[i].Intensities
    76	```
    77	
    78	`TraceType.TIC` is a real enum member (used at `XIC/XicReader.cs:119` with `TraceType.MassRange`;
    79	the TIC CV term `MS:1000235 "total ion current chromatogram"` is already in
    80	`OntologyMapping.cs:1051-1059` under the `"tic"` key). `-1, -1` means "whole run". The returned
    81	`ChromatogramSignal` exposes `Times` (List<double>, **minutes** — Thermo native, matching
    82	`UO:0000031` and the ground-truth time scale 0.0049..0.487) and `Intensities` (List<double>).
    83	
    84	### Verified 1:1 alignment (the key fact that shapes the snippet)
    85	
    86	The ground-truth TIC has **exactly 48 points for 48 scans**, and elementwise:
    87	`TIC.time[i] == spectrum.time[i]` (true), `TIC.ms_level[i] == spectrum.ms_level[i]` (true),
    88	monotonic non-decreasing time (true). So the device TIC trace yields one value per scan in scan
    89	order — pair it directly with the per-scan record already built in the loop.
    90	
    91	### Recommended snippet (drop into `MzPeakSpectrumWriter.Write`, after the scan loop)
    92	
    93	```csharp
    94	// Device TIC over the whole run (minutes, one value per scan, scan order).
    95	raw.SelectInstrument(Device.MS, 1);
    96	var ticSettings = new ChromatogramTraceSettings(TraceType.TIC);
    97	var ticData  = raw.GetChromatogramData(new IChromatogramSettings[] { ticSettings }, -1, -1);
    98	var ticTrace = ChromatogramSignal.FromChromatogramData(ticData);
    99	
   100	// trace[0] is the MS TIC; pair its (time,intensity) with each record's ms_level by ordinal.
   101	var chromTime      = new List<double>();   // f64, minutes  -> point.time
   102	var chromIntensity = new List<float>();    // f32           -> point.intensity
   103	var chromMsLevel   = new List<long>();     // i64           -> point.ms_level  (per-scan ms_level)
   104	if (ticTrace.Length > 0 && ticTrace[0].Times.Count == records.Count)
   105	{
   106	    for (int i = 0; i < records.Count; i++)
   107	    {
   108	        chromTime.Add(ticTrace[0].Times[i]);
   109	        chromIntensity.Add((float)ticTrace[0].Intensities[i]);
   110	        chromMsLevel.Add(records[i].MsLevel);
   111	    }
   112	}
   113	// Fallback if the device trace length != scan count (filtered MS levels / range subset):
   114	// re-key by matching ticTrace[0].Scans (scan numbers) to records by scan number, OR fall back to
   115	// records[i].Time + (float)records[i].TotalIonCurrent. Note the fallback intensity will NOT
   116	// match the reference device TIC for MS1 — acceptable only when the device trace is unavailable.
   117	```
   118	
   119	`records[i].MsLevel` and `records[i].Time` already exist (`MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs:54-58,186-187`).
   120	The TIC carries the **scan's** ms_level (1 or 2), confirmed against ground truth.
   121	
   122	**Confidence:** HIGH — exact API call grepped at MzMlSpectrumWriter.cs:935; 1:1 alignment proven by
   123	pyarrow elementwise comparison against the real reference archive.
